9/23/24, 10:24â€¯AM - Akshara CCE: import java.util.Scanner;

public class Main {
    public static void main(String[] args) {
        Scanner sc = new Scanner(System.in);
        System.out.print("Enter the number of rows: ");
        int n = sc.nextInt();
        
        char startChar = (char) ('A' + (26 - n)); // Determine the starting character

        for (int i = 0; i < n; i++) {
            for (int j = 0; j <= i; j++) {
                System.out.print((char) (startChar + i));
            }
            System.out.println();
        }

        sc.close();
    }
}

9/26/24, 2:12â€¯PM - Kiran Kumar CCE: 1. Functions Provided by Operating Systems:

Process Management: Creation, scheduling, and termination of processes.

Memory Management: Allocation and deallocation of memory to processes.

File System Management: Managing files, directories, and permissions.

Device Management: Handling device I/O operations through device drivers.

Security and Access Control: Ensuring authorized access to resources.

User Interface: Providing command-line or graphical user interface.

Networking: Facilitating communication between processes over a network.

Error Detection and Handling: Monitoring and handling errors.


2. Dual Mode Operation & Its Need:

Dual Mode Operation: Operating systems operate in two modes: User Mode and Kernel Mode.

User Mode: Limited access to system resources to prevent accidental or malicious operations.

Kernel Mode: Full access to system resources and execution of privileged instructions.


Need for Dual Mode:

Provides a mechanism to protect the operating system from user programs.

Prevents malicious or buggy applications from disrupting system operations.

Ensures system stability and security by controlling resource access.



3. System Calls for Communication Control:

socket(): Create a socket for communication.

bind(): Bind a socket to an address.

listen(): Listen for connections on a socket.

accept(): Accept a connection on a socket.

connect(): Establish a connection to a socket.

send() and recv(): Send and receive messages over a socket.

shutdown(): Shutdown part or all of a connection.

close(): Close a socket descriptor.


4. System Boot:

System Boot Process:

1. BIOS/UEFI Initialization: The Basic Input/Output System or Unified Extensible Firmware Interface initializes hardware and performs POST (Power-On Self Test).


2. Boot Loader Execution: BIOS/UEFI loads the boot loader (e.g., GRUB) from the bootable device.


3. Kernel Loading: The boot loader loads the operating system kernel into memory.


4. Kernel Initialization: The kernel initializes system components and loads essential services and drivers.


5. System Startup: The kernel starts the init process (PID 1), which loads other system and user-level processes.




5. Use of fork() and exec() System Calls:

fork(): Creates a new process by duplicating the calling process. The new process is called the child process and has a unique PID.

Returns 0 to the child process and the child PID to the parent process.


exec(): Replaces the current process image with a new process image. Used to run a new program within the context of the current process.

After exec(), the process continues with the new program, and the previous program is completely replaced.



Example Use:

pid_t pid = fork();
if (pid == 0) {
    // Child process
    execvp("ls", args); // Replaces child process with 'ls' command
} else {
    // Parent process continues
    wait(NULL); // Waits for the child process to finish
}

6. Interrupts:

Definition: An interrupt is a signal to the processor emitted by hardware or software indicating an event that needs immediate attention.

Types of Interrupts:

Hardware Interrupts: Triggered by hardware devices like keyboard, mouse, or disk.

Software Interrupts: Triggered by software instructions like system calls or exceptions.


Purpose: Allows the CPU to respond to external events or changes in state, ensuring efficient multitasking and resource management.


7. Difference Between Process & Thread:

Process:

Independent unit with its own memory space and resources.

Contains multiple threads.

High overhead for context switching.


Thread:

Smaller unit of execution within a process.

Shares memory and resources with other threads in the same process.

Lower overhead for context switching.



8. Context Switch:

Definition: The process of saving the state of a currently running process or thread and restoring the state of another process or thread to allow it to execute.

Purpose: Enables multitasking by switching between multiple processes or threads efficiently.

Components Saved:

CPU registers, program counter, and stack pointer.

Memory management information.



9. Process Scheduling:

Definition: The method by which an operating system decides which processes get to use the CPU and for how long.

Types of Schedulers:

Long-Term Scheduler (Job Scheduler): Decides which jobs or processes are admitted to the system for execution.

Short-Term Scheduler (CPU Scheduler): Selects from among the ready processes in memory which one to execute next.

Medium-Term Scheduler: Temporarily removes processes from main memory to reduce the degree of multiprogramming (swapping).


Scheduling Algorithms:

First-Come, First-Served (FCFS)

Shortest Job Next (SJN)

Round Robin (RR)

Priority Scheduling
9/26/24, 2:17â€¯PM - Kiran Kumar CCE: 10 (b) Distinguish between Multiprogramming and Time-Sharing Environment:

Multiprogramming:

1. Definition:

Multiprogramming is a technique in which multiple programs are loaded into memory and executed by the CPU simultaneously. It maximizes CPU utilization by running another program when the current one is waiting for I/O operations.



2. Objective:

To keep the CPU busy as much as possible by executing multiple programs concurrently.



3. Execution:

Programs are executed based on priority, and the CPU switches between them when a program is waiting for an I/O operation.



4. Response Time:

Response time is not a primary concern. The focus is on maximizing CPU utilization.



5. Example:

Batch processing systems where multiple jobs are processed in batches without user interaction.




Time-Sharing:

1. Definition:

Time-sharing is a logical extension of multiprogramming where multiple users can interact with the system simultaneously. The CPU time is divided into small time slices, and each user gets a time slice to execute their program.



2. Objective:

To provide a fast response to users by allowing multiple users to interact with the system concurrently, ensuring that each user feels they have their own dedicated machine.



3. Execution:

Each user gets a small time slice in a round-robin fashion. If a user's time slice expires, the CPU switches to the next user.



4. Response Time:

Short response time is crucial to ensure that users experience quick and interactive processing.



5. Example:

Unix/Linux systems where multiple users can access the system at the same time and run different commands interactively.
9/26/24, 2:20â€¯PM - Kiran Kumar CCE: 11 (a) Illustrate in Detail about Storage I/O Structure by Describing its Hierarchy Structure:

Storage I/O Structure Hierarchy:

1. I/O Devices: Physical hardware devices like hard disks, SSDs, and optical drives.


2. I/O Controller: Interface between the I/O devices and the computer system. Manages device communication and data transfer.


3. Device Drivers: Software that controls a particular type of device attached to the computer. Provides a layer of abstraction for the OS to interact with hardware.


4. I/O Scheduler: Manages the queue of pending I/O requests, decides the order in which I/O operations should be performed.


5. File System: Organizes and manages files and directories, handling file creation, deletion, and metadata.


6. Logical I/O: Interface provided by the operating system to perform higher-level I/O operations, like file reading and writing.


7. System Call Interface: Interface for user programs to request I/O operations from the operating system.


8. User Programs: Programs initiated by the user that require I/O operations, like reading or writing data.



Hierarchy Structure:

User Programs
     â†“
System Call Interface
     â†“
Logical I/O
     â†“
File System
     â†“
I/O Scheduler
     â†“
Device Drivers
     â†“
I/O Controller
     â†“
I/O Devices

11 (b) What are System Calls? State & Explain the Types of System Calls.

System Calls:

System calls are programming interfaces provided by the operating system that allow user programs to request services from the kernel. They serve as a bridge between the user space and kernel space, enabling interaction with hardware resources and system-level operations.


Types of System Calls:

1. Process Control:

Examples: fork(), exec(), exit(), wait().

Used to create, execute, and terminate processes.



2. File Management:

Examples: open(), close(), read(), write(), unlink().

Perform operations related to file handling such as opening, reading, writing, and closing files.



3. Device Management:

Examples: ioctl(), read(), write().

Involve operations on devices like reading from or writing to a device, or configuring device settings.



4. Information Maintenance:

Examples: getpid(), alarm(), gettimeofday().

Retrieve or set system data, like getting the process ID, setting system date/time, etc.



5. Communication:

Examples: pipe(), shmget(), msgget(), socket().

Manage communication between processes either on the same machine or across different machines.




12 (a) Explain in Detail about Inter-Process Communication.

Inter-Process Communication (IPC):

IPC is a mechanism that allows processes to communicate with each other and synchronize their actions. It is essential for coordinating processes that need to share data or resources.


Types of IPC:

1. Pipes:

Unidirectional communication channel between a parent and child process. Data written by one process can be read by the other.



2. Message Queues:

Allows processes to send and receive messages, enabling them to exchange data in the form of messages.



3. Shared Memory:

Allows multiple processes to access the same memory space. This is the fastest form of IPC because data does not need to be copied between processes.



4. Semaphores:

Synchronization tool used to control access to a common resource by multiple processes to avoid race conditions.



5. Sockets:

Allows communication between processes over a network. Useful for inter-process communication between systems.




Benefits of IPC:

Data Sharing: Enables sharing of data between processes without duplicating memory.

Modularity: Allows dividing complex applications into simpler processes.

Concurrency: Supports concurrent execution of processes.


12 (b) What is a Process? Discuss Components of Process and Various States of a Process with the Help of a Process State Transition Diagram.

Process:

A process is a program in execution, including the program code and its activity. It represents the basic unit of work in an operating system.


Components of a Process:

1. Program Code (Text Section): The actual code or instructions to be executed.


2. Program Counter: A register that stores the address of the next instruction to be executed.


3. Process Stack: Contains temporary data such as function parameters, return addresses, and local variables.


4. Data Section: Contains global variables and dynamically allocated memory.


5. Process Control Block (PCB): Contains information about the process state, process ID, program counter, registers, memory limits, and list of open files.



Process States:

1. New: The process is being created.


2. Ready: The process is waiting to be assigned to the CPU.


3. Running: Instructions are being executed.


4. Waiting (Blocked): The process is waiting for an event to occur (like I/O completion).


5. Terminated: The process has finished execution.



Process State Transition Diagram:

+-----------+                    +------------+
       |   New     |------------------->|  Ready     |
       +-----------+                    +------------+
             |                               |
             |                               |
             v                               v
       +-----------+                    +------------+
       | Running   |------------------->| Terminated |
       +-----------+<-------------------|            |
             |                               ^
             |                               |
             v                               |
       +-----------+                    +------------+
       | Waiting   |------------------->|  Ready     |
       +-----------+                    +------------+

9/27/24, 9:06â€¯AM - Gayathri CCE: Role of a Security Mechanism in OSI Security Architecture
Security mechanisms in the OSI model protect data from unauthorized access and ensure integrity, confidentiality, and authenticity. These include encryption, authentication, and access control methods to protect the communication layers.

Substitution and Transposition Techniques in Cryptography

Substitution: Replaces plaintext elements with ciphertext (e.g., Caesar Cipher).
Transposition: Rearranges the order of plaintext characters to form ciphertext (e.g., Rail Fence Cipher).
Two Classical Encryption Techniques

Caesar Cipher: Shifts characters in the plaintext by a fixed number.
VigenÃ¨re Cipher: Uses a keyword to shift the alphabet based on corresponding keyword letters.
Key Features of the Network Security Model
The key features include confidentiality, integrity, authentication, access control, and non-repudiation. These ensure that data is protected, authenticated, and delivered securely across the network.

Main Types of Security Attacks

Passive Attacks: Eavesdropping, traffic analysis.
Active Attacks: Modification of data, replay, denial of service.
Steganography and How It Differs from Cryptography

Steganography: Hides the existence of the message within other data (e.g., hiding text in an image).
Cryptography: Encrypts the message to make it unreadable without the decryption key.
Concept of Algebraic Structures in Cryptography
Algebraic structures like groups, rings, and fields are used in cryptography to develop complex encryption algorithms, especially in public-key cryptography (e.g., RSA uses modular arithmetic).

How Simplified DES Differs from Standard DES
Simplified DES (S-DES) is a reduced version of DES designed for educational purposes. It uses a 10-bit key and operates on 8-bit blocks, while standard DES uses a 56-bit key and operates on 64-bit blocks.

Expand DES and Its Key Length
DES stands for Data Encryption Standard, and it has a key length of 56 bits.

### Question 10: **Explain the principles of information theory and its application in modern cryptography. How does it relate to entropy and data compression?**

**Information Theory**  
Information theory, founded by Claude Shannon, deals with the quantification, storage, and communication of information. In cryptography, it plays a critical role in understanding the security and efficiency of communication systems. Some of the key principles of information theory in cryptography are:

- **Entropy**: 
   - Entropy measures the unpredictability or randomness of information. In cryptographic terms, it indicates how hard it is to guess the next bit in a sequence of data.
   - Higher entropy implies more randomness, making encryption schemes harder to break because attackers can't predict patterns in the ciphertext.
   - For example, if a message has low entropy, it has a lot of redundancy or predictable patterns, making it easier to decrypt without a key. Good cryptographic algorithms aim to produce ciphertext with high entropy, simulating randomness.

- **Redundancy**: 
   - Cryptographic systems also aim to reduce redundancy in data, as redundancy provides clues that an attacker might exploit.
   - If the ciphertext or encryption process is predictable, even slightly, it opens avenues for cryptanalysis (such as frequency analysis).

- **Data Compression**:  
   - Compression and encryption are both means of transforming data, but they serve different purposes. Compression reduces the size of data by eliminating redundancy (e.g., Huffman coding), while encryption scrambles data to prevent unauthorized access.
   - In some systems, compressing data before encryption is advisable, as compressed data typically has higher entropy. This can further enhance the security of the cryptosystem since patterns are less detectable.

**Relation to Cryptography**:
- **Encryption and Information Leakage**:  
   Information theory helps assess how much information might leak during encryption. Ideally, encryption should not reveal anything about the plaintext other than its length.
  
- **Error Detection and Correction**:  
   Information theory is also vital for detecting and correcting errors in communication, ensuring data integrity. Cryptographic protocols often use these techniques to ensure that even if encrypted data is tampered with, the tampering can be detected.

### Application:
Modern cryptographic algorithms, especially in block ciphers and stream ciphers, are designed with principles from information theory to ensure high entropy, no redundancy, and minimal leakage of information. These principles guide the development of secure cryptographic systems, ensuring that even if an attacker intercepts the ciphertext, they cannot derive useful information without the decryption key.

---

### Question 11: **Organize the challenges in implementing a robust network security model in todayâ€™s digital environment. How can organizations ensure effective security across all layers?**

**Challenges in Implementing a Robust Network Security Model**  
In today's complex digital landscape, network security is more challenging than ever. Several factors make implementing a robust network security model difficult:

1. **Evolving Threats**:
   - Cyber threats evolve constantly, with new attack vectors emerging, such as **ransomware**, **phishing**, and **advanced persistent threats (APTs)**. Attackers often use zero-day vulnerabilities, which are security flaws unknown to the developers, making it difficult for organizations to respond in time.
  
2. **Complex Networks**:
   - Modern networks are complex, with distributed systems, cloud computing, mobile devices, and IoT (Internet of Things) all interacting. Securing such a heterogeneous environment is a significant challenge. Attack surfaces expand, and securing every node becomes a daunting task.

3. **Remote Work and BYOD (Bring Your Own Device)**:
   - With the rise of remote work and BYOD policies, employees access corporate networks from personal devices that may not be secure. This increases the risk of unauthorized access or malware infecting the organization's network.

4. **Data Privacy Regulations**:
   - Compliance with data privacy regulations like **GDPR** or **HIPAA** requires businesses to secure personal data. Organizations must ensure that their security models adhere to these strict regulations or face heavy penalties.

5. **Social Engineering Attacks**:
   - Security models are often breached through social engineering tactics, where attackers manipulate individuals into divulging confidential information or bypassing security protocols. Phishing attacks are a common example.

6. **Encryption and Key Management**:
   - While encryption ensures data confidentiality, managing encryption keys securely across an organization can be challenging. If keys are not managed properly, encrypted data can become vulnerable.

**How Organizations Can Ensure Effective Security**:

1. **Multi-Layered Security Model (Defense-in-Depth)**:
   - Implementing multiple layers of security, also known as **defense-in-depth**, helps protect against different attack vectors. These layers include firewalls, intrusion detection/prevention systems (IDS/IPS), encryption, and endpoint security.
   - By ensuring that even if one layer is breached, additional layers can mitigate the threat.

2. **Zero Trust Architecture**:
   - **Zero Trust** assumes that threats can come from both inside and outside the network. Hence, it requires continuous verification of user identities and strict access controls.
   - Multi-factor authentication (MFA) and least privilege access are critical components of a Zero Trust security model.

3. **Regular Security Audits and Vulnerability Assessments**:
   - Regular assessments help identify weak points in the network. Penetration testing simulates attacks to discover vulnerabilities before attackers do.
   - **Patch management** ensures that known vulnerabilities are addressed quickly by updating systems with security patches.

4. **Data Encryption**:
   - Encrypting sensitive data both at rest (stored data) and in transit (data being transmitted) ensures that even if attackers gain access, they cannot read the data without the decryption key.

5. **Security Awareness Training**:
   - Since human error often leads to security breaches, regular training for employees on identifying phishing attempts, using strong passwords, and following security protocols is essential.

---

### Question 12: **Distinguish the various modes of operation for block ciphers (ECB, CBC, CTR). Discuss the advantages and disadvantages of each mode. Analyze the examples of when each mode would be appropriately used in a secure communication system.**

**Electronic Codebook (ECB)**:  
   - **How It Works**: In ECB mode, each block of plaintext is encrypted independently, without any relation to other blocks.
   - **Advantages**: Simple and fast since blocks are processed individually.
   - **Disadvantages**: Identical plaintext blocks produce identical ciphertext blocks, which makes it insecure for large datasets as patterns in the plaintext become visible. Not suitable for encrypting long or repetitive data.
   - **Use Cases**: Useful for encrypting short messages or individual keys (e.g., in databases where uniqueness is guaranteed), but generally not recommended for large data.

**Cipher Block Chaining (CBC)**:  
   - **How It Works**: Each plaintext block is XORed with the previous ciphertext block before being encrypted. An initialization vector (IV) is used for the first block to ensure randomness.
   - **Advantages**: More secure than ECB because identical plaintext blocks will not produce identical ciphertext blocks. It provides confidentiality for repeated blocks.
   - **Disadvantages**: It is vulnerable to bit-flipping attacks, where changes in one block affect the decryption of the subsequent block. Also, CBC is sequential, so it cannot be parallelized.
   - **Use Cases**: Suitable for file encryption and situations where data integrity is not as important (e.g., secure email communication, VPN encryption).

**Counter Mode (CTR)**:  
   - **How It Works**: A counter value is used for each block, which is then encrypted to produce a keystream. The plaintext is XORed with the keystream to produce the ciphertext.
   - **Advantages**: CTR mode can be parallelized, making it much faster in implementations requiring high performance (e.g., hardware accelerators). It ensures the ciphertext is indistinguishable from random data.
   - **Disadvantages**: If the counter is reused (nonce-reuse), it results in catastrophic failures, making the ciphertext vulnerable to attacks. Key management is crucial.
   - **Use Cases**: Ideal for high-throughput encryption tasks, like streaming services, disk encryption, and VPNs.

**Or**

**Analyze the Data Encryption Standard (DES)**:  
   DES is a symmetric-key block cipher that encrypts data in 64-bit blocks using a 56-bit key. It operates through a series of permutations and substitutions. 

- **Key Schedule**: DES generates 16 subkeys from the main 56-bit key by applying shifts and permutations.
  
- **Encryption Process**: 
   - DES uses 16 rounds of **Feistel structure**, where each round involves bit-shuffling (permutations), XOR operations, and a combination of substitution boxes (S-boxes).
   - The plaintext is divided into two halves, and the right half is expanded and XORed with a subkey, and the result is passed through S-boxes to generate a new right half.

- **Decryption Process**: The same process is followed in reverse order, using the same subkeys in reverse.

**Strengths**:
   - DES was highly efficient for hardware-based encryption and was widely adopted for secure communications in its time.
   
**Weaknesses**:
   - The 56-bit key length is insufficient against modern brute-force attacks, making DES insecure.
   - Advances in cryptanalysis, such as differential and linear cryptanalysis, have weakened the security of DES.
   
**Why DES Is Insecure Today**:  
   With today's computing power, DESâ€™s 56-bit key length can be cracked in a short amount of time. A brute-force attack, where all possible key combinations are tried, can break DES. For this reason, DES has largely been replaced by more secure algorithms like AES (Advanced Encryption Standard), which uses key lengths

1. **Role of a Security Mechanism in OSI Security Architecture**:
   - Security mechanisms enforce security services like confidentiality, integrity, and authentication to protect data from attacks across the OSI layers.

2. **Comparison of Substitution and Transposition Techniques**:
   - Substitution replaces characters with other characters while maintaining their position, whereas transposition rearranges the position of characters without altering the characters themselves.

3. **Two Classical Encryption Techniques**:
   - **Caesar Cipher**: Shifts each letter in the plaintext by a fixed number.
   - **VigenÃ¨re Cipher**: Uses a keyword to shift letters by varying amounts.

4. **Key Features of the Network Security Model**:
   - Ensures confidentiality, integrity, authentication, non-repudiation, and access control over network communications.

5. **Main Types of Security Attacks**:
   - **Passive Attacks**: Eavesdropping on communication.
   - **Active Attacks**: Modifying or disrupting communication (e.g., denial of service).

6. **Steganography vs. Cryptography**:
   - Steganography hides the existence of a message, while cryptography protects the content of the message.

7. **Group in Algebraic Structures**:
   - A group is a set with a binary operation that satisfies closure, associativity, identity element, and inverse properties.

8. **Difference Between S-DES and DES**:
   - S-DES uses 8-bit blocks and 10-bit keys, while standard DES uses 64-bit blocks and 56-bit keys.

9. **DES Expansion and Key Length**:
   - **DES**: Data Encryption Standard.
   - **Key Length**: 56-bit key, with a total of 64 bits (including 8 parity bits).

9/27/24, 2:39â€¯PM - Mythreyan SECE: import java.util.Arrays;

public class TaskDistribution {

    public static int minMaxPairSum(int N, int[] difficulties) {
        // Step 1: Sort the array
        Arrays.sort(difficulties);
        
        // Step 2: Initialize a variable to track the maximum pair sum
        int maxPairSum = 0;
        
        // Step 3: Form pairs from the smallest and largest, and compute their sums
        for (int i = 0; i < N / 2; i++) {
            int currentPairSum = difficulties[i] + difficulties[N - 1 - i];
            maxPairSum = Math.max(maxPairSum, currentPairSum);
        }
        
        // Return the maximum pair sum found
        return maxPairSum;
    }

    public static void main(String[] args) {
        // Example input
        int N = 6;
        int[] difficulties = {3, 5, 2, 3, 8, 7};
        
        // Calling the method and printing the result
        int result = minMaxPairSum(N, difficulties);
        System.out.println(result);  // Output: 10
    }
}

        // Step 1: Sort the array
        Arrays.sort(input2);
        
        // Step 2: Calculate the minimum sum of the first two elements
        // Ensure that the array has at least 2 elements
        if (input1 < 2) {
            throw new IllegalArgumentException("The number of items must be at least 2.");
        }
        
        // Step 3: Return the sum of the two smallest items
        return input2[0] + input2[1];
    }
    // Read only region end 
}

        int[] items = {3, 5, 1}; // Example input
        int result = userMainCode.shoppingList(items.length, items);
        System.out.println("Minimum possible sum of any two consecutive items: " + result); // Output: 4
    }
}

public class Permutations {
    // Method to calculate factorial
    private static int factorial(int n) {
        if (n <= 1) return 1;
        return n * factorial(n - 1);
    }

    public static int countPermutations(String input) {
        int length = input.length();
        // Return the factorial of the length of the string
        return factorial(length);
    }

    public static void main(String[] args) {
        String input = "abc"; // Example input
        int result = countPermutations(input);
        System.out.println("Number of permutations: " + result); // Output: 6
    }
}

9/27/24, 2:49â€¯PM - Sathya Ruba CCE: public class PermutationWithFixedVowels {

    public static int countPermutations(String S) {
        int vowels = 0, consonants = 0;
        for (char c : S.toCharArray()) {
            if ("AEIOUaeiou".indexOf(c) != -1) vowels++;
            else consonants++;
        }
        return consonants == 0 ? 0 : factorial(consonants);
    }

    private static int factorial(int n) {
        int result = 1;
        for (int i = 2; i <= n; i++) result *= i;
        return result;
    }

    public static void main(String[] args) {
        System.out.println(countPermutations("ABC"));  // Output: 2
    }
}

9/27/24, 2:51â€¯PM - Rithesh CCE: import java.util.ArrayList;

class UserMainCode {
    public int[] exponentialseries(int input1, int input2, int input3) {
        ArrayList<Integer> series = new ArrayList<>();
        int currentTerm = input1;
        
        while (currentTerm <= input3) {
            series.add(currentTerm);
            currentTerm *= input2;
        }
        
        return series.stream().mapToInt(i -> i).toArray();
    }

    public static void main(String[] args) {
        UserMainCode userMainCode = new UserMainCode();
        int[] result = userMainCode.exponentialseries(2, 3, 100);
        
        for (int num : result) {
            System.out.print(num + " ");
        }
    }
}

9/27/24, 2:59â€¯PM - Akshara CCE: import java.util.ArrayList;

public class UserMainCode {
    public int[] exponentialSeries(int input1, int input2, int input3) {
        int A = input1; // First term
        double R = input2; // Common ratio
        int Z = input3; // Upper limit
        
        ArrayList<Integer> series = new ArrayList<>();
        
        // Start generating terms
        double term = A; // Current term starts with the first term A
        while (term <= Z) {
            series.add((int) term); // Add current term to the series
            term *= R; // Calculate the next term
        }
        
        // Convert the ArrayList to an int array
        return series.stream().mapToInt(i -> i).toArray();
    }

    public static void main(String[] args) {
        UserMainCode umc = new UserMainCode();
        int[] result = umc.exponentialSeries(2, 3, 50); // Example input
        System.out.println(Arrays.toString(result)); // Output: [2, 6, 18]
    }
}
9/27/24, 3:05â€¯PM - Subash CCE: import java.util.*;

class UserMainCode {

    // Function to find the minimum possible sum of any two consecutive items
    public int shoppingList(int input1, int[] input2) {
        // Step 1: Sort the array to rearrange items for minimal adjacent sums
        Arrays.sort(input2);

        // Step 2: Initialize a variable to track the minimum sum of consecutive items
        int minSum = Integer.MAX_VALUE;

        // Step 3: Find the smallest sum between consecutive items
        for (int i = 1; i < input1; i++) {
            // Calculate the sum of the current item and the previous one
            int currentSum = input2[i] + input2[i - 1];

            // Track the minimum sum found
            minSum = Math.min(minSum, currentSum);
        }

        // Step 4: Return the smallest sum found
        return minSum;
    }
}
9/27/24, 3:07â€¯PM - Rithesh CCE: import java.util.Arrays;
import java.util.Scanner;

class UserMainCode {
    public int shoppingList(int input1, int[] input2) {
        Arrays.sort(input2);
        return input2[0] + input2[1];
    }

    public static void main(String[] args) {
        Scanner sc = new Scanner(System.in);
        System.out.print("Enter the number of items: ");
        int input1 = sc.nextInt();
        int[] input2 = new int[input1];
        System.out.print("Enter the items: ");
        for (int i = 0; i < input1; i++) {
            input2[i] = sc.nextInt();
        }
        UserMainCode userMainCode = new UserMainCode();
        int result = userMainCode.shoppingList(input1, input2);
        System.out.println("Minimum possible sum of any two consecutive items: " + result);
        sc.close();
    }
}

10/26/24, 8:40â€¯PM - Pavithra CCE: Greetings!

We are pleased to announce that the IGEN Green Day Celebration Week will be held from 22nd October to 29th October 2024. This event aims to promote Climate change, environmental awareness and sustainable practices in alignment with the United Nations Sustainable Development Goals (UNSDGs).

In this regard, all Class Advisers and Mentors are requested to ensure the active participation of your students (20 each) in various events planned for the week. Participation is mandatory for all students to promote environmental stewardship and sustainability within our campus or home etc.,

Procedures for Participation, Certificates, and Awards:

Registration:

Students must register for the events using the provided Google form or through the college portal by 22/10/2024. Advisor/Tutors should ensure all your students are aware of the registration deadlines.

 Attendance and Engagement:

Participation in at least one key event is required to be eligible for a participation certificate. These events will include pledge on your favourite goals, reels photograph seminars, workshops, competitions, and green initiatives like tree planting drives, plastic awareness champion, water conservation, energy conservation, food waste reduction carbon emission reduction practices etc.,

 Event Guidelines:

Each event will follow specific guidelines that will be communicated in advance. Students must adhere to these guidelines to be eligible for awards and certificates.

The participants to follow below procedure (Post the action between Oct 22 to 29 Oct 2024)

1) Join the #igen green day FB Group https://www.facebook.com/groups/igengreenday   

2) Select your favourite SDG Goals and plan the green pledge related to your favourite goal. More about SDG Goal watch video https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=AG0zG6u3xrM

2) Select the green action which can change your habit and take PLEDGE to implement the action. You can choose green action from website https://greenday.theigen.org/ or select your own green action, GREEN ACTIONS ALSO LISTED AT THE END OF THE DOCUMENTS

3) Complete the action and post the video or photo (Post the action between Oct 22 to 29th Oct 2024)   @ FB group https://www.facebook.com/groups/igengreenday with the write up of action and the follow the hashtag #igenGreenday #igenGreenday2024 #globalgoals #green #sdgs #pledge4green add one more hash tag #seceigengreenday #sdg4eshwar

4) Upload the details in the following google form link - https://forms.gle/oEKAHMc7uD9Khiob8

 

Certificates:

Certificates of Participation will be issued to students who fulfill the required criteria and actively participate in at least one event during the week. These certificates will bear the UNSDG Ring symbol, signifying their contribution to the global sustainability movement.

 Awards:

Special awards will be presented to students and faculty who demonstrate exceptional commitment and leadership in promoting sustainability during the event week. These awards will be conferred during the closing ceremony.

We encourage all advisers and mentors to guide your wards through the registration and participation process and ensure maximum engagement in the Green Day Celebration Week.

Letâ€™s work together to build a greener and more sustainable future!

10/28/24, 12:47â€¯PM - Gayathri CCE: class Solution {
    public boolean solution(int[] values, int K, int L) {
        int n = values.length;
        for (int i = L; i < n; i++) {
            if (values[i - L] == values[i] - L) {
                return false;
            }
        }
        return values[n - 1] == K;
    }
}
second
10/28/24, 12:54â€¯PM - Gayathri CCE: class Solution {
    public double solution(double[] predicted, double[] observed) {
        double sumSquaredError = 0.0;
        int n = predicted.length;
        
        for (int i = 0; i < n; i++) {
            double error = predicted[i] - observed[i];
            sumSquaredError += error * error;
        }
        
        return Math.sqrt(sumSquaredError / n);
    }
}
